TY  - JOUR
T1  - Technological Resources and the Direction of Corporate Diversification: Toward an Integration of the Resource-Based View and Transaction Cost Economics
AU  - Silverman, Brian S.
Y1  - 1999/08/01
PY  - 1999
DA  - 1999/08/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.45.8.1109
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.45.8.1109
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 1109
EP  - 1124
VL  - 45
IS  - 8
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - This study considers how a firm's resource base affects the choice of industries into which the firm diversifies. It offers two main extensions of prior research. First, it operationalizes technological resources at a more detailed level than in prior studies, thereby enabling a more stringent analysis of the direction of diversification. This analysis shows that the predictive power of the ?resource-based view of the firm? is greatly improved when resources are measured at a finer level. Second, the study integrates principles from transaction cost economics into resource-based predictions concerning diversification. In particular, it tests the common assumption that rent-generating resources are too asset specific to allow contracting. The findings point to circumstances where resources can be and are exploited through contracting rather than through diversification.
AB  - This study considers how a firm's resource base affects the choice of industries into which the firm diversifies. It offers two main extensions of prior research. First, it operationalizes technological resources at a more detailed level than in prior studies, thereby enabling a more stringent analysis of the direction of diversification. This analysis shows that the predictive power of the ?resource-based view of the firm? is greatly improved when resources are measured at a finer level. Second, the study integrates principles from transaction cost economics into resource-based predictions concerning diversification. In particular, it tests the common assumption that rent-generating resources are too asset specific to allow contracting. The findings point to circumstances where resources can be and are exploited through contracting rather than through diversification.
